Not exactly jobs related but I did not want to pollute the <#C04PLQMUM> . 

I am making a job advertisement for software developer (junior to mid for iOS) and my boss wants to have every person that applies to post CV + a full page answering 2 questions so we can get a feel if "they are interested". I am against the 2 questions since most people won't bother (and rightly so) but in any case since he wants that I'll put it in. 

What 2 software development questions could I put to filter out non-developers? I would prefer short ones to not bother them too much with filling a full page

that's exactly what I said, he won't listen
so I'm like "so be it, we won't find anyone for at least a couple of months"

<@U09T8SFG8>: Ask them to rate themselves between 1-10
Before you get into anything technical
It gives you a good idea of what they think of themselves vs what they know

Someone who ranks themselves as say a 9, but can’t answers most questions a mid should know… tells you they probably aren’t going to be outgoing to learn more/new things and probably won’t take criticism well.
Unless say that person is a GDE or equivalent stature then sure
Eh, isn't that way too open for interpretation?
not if you say 9 or 10
Sounds like the same as asking "What are your weaknesses?"
<@U04VA47NB>: I’m too much of a winner
I just keep winning and winning
I have no weaknesses
I just can’t stop winning.
my weakness is the inability for mere mortals to comprehend how great i am

What austin is suggesting though is how hard we should rate you. A mid level applicant should likely think of themselves somewhere between 4 and 7 out of 10 just generally. A senior should probably be between 6 and 8 or so. These aren’t hard numbers just an expectation of what I would expect to hear. The problem is that some people like to say 9 and 10 but can’t tell me how an Intent is used as IPC nor can the explain handlers work even after I lead them to explain what the looper is. Other examples are ‘senior’ devs that use asynctask exclusively, don’t know how to find memory leaks, can not explain the volatile keyword.
hey, I rate myself as 9 now that I can answer all those q's :smile:

not that any of those are exclusive things you absolutely must know just generally stating that given a long list of what I would consider core knowledge a surprising number of people that rate themselves highly tend not to have much knowledge of android.
thx, lesson learned
I was told to over-rate rather than under-rate
